        introduction: "Pornic is an authentic and charming seaside resort on the Côte de Jade (Jade Coast), named for the emerald colour of its waters. The medieval castle of Bluebeard (13th century), perched on a rocky spur overlooking the old port, gives the town its iconic silhouette. Pornic charms visitors with its picturesque fishing port where trawlers sit alongside pleasure boats, its fine sand coves (Plage de la Source, Plage du Château), its Alliance thalassotherapy centre (one of the most renowned on the Atlantic coast) and its GR8 coastal paths offering breathtaking panoramas. The town is also known for the Gautier-Debotté chocolate maker and the Beillevaire dairy whose butter is exported across France. The Nantes — Pornic journey is used by locals at weekends heading for the coast, thalassotherapy guests, and families holidaying at Jade Coast campsites. It is a quick and pleasant drive through Muscadet wine country before reaching the iodine-rich coastal air.",
        itineraire: "Your driver leaves Nantes via the southern ring road (Porte de Rezé exit) then takes the D751, nicknamed the Route Bleue. This road first crosses the Muscadet wine country with its characteristic rows of vines typical of the Nantes area, passing through Bouaye and Port-Saint-Père. You then pass through Saint-Hilaire-de-Chaléons and Arthon-en-Retz before reaching the coastline. The first ocean views appear at La Bernerie-en-Retz, a charming small seaside resort. You then follow the coast to Pornic. Arrival is via Rue de la Marine towards the old port, or via Route de la Noëveillard for the thalassotherapy centre. The entire journey is free with no tolls. Allow 40 minutes outside peak hours, 50-55 minutes on summer Friday evenings when locals head for the coast.",
        conseils: "The Alliance thalassotherapy centre in Pornic offers 1 to 6-day cures and day treatments (heated seawater bath from €25). Book treatments in advance during summer. The coastal path (GR8) between Pornic and La Bernerie-en-Retz offers 8 km of spectacular walking: your driver can drop you at one end and collect you at the other. Pornic castle is not open to visitors (private property) but the view from the old port is magnificent, especially at sunset. La Poissonnerie du Môle restaurant on the port serves ultra-fresh seafood at reasonable prices. Pornic markets (Thursday and Sunday mornings) are excellent. In summer, a maritime shuttle between Pornic and Noirmoutier operates on certain days — check with the tourist office.",
